{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="checklist-year-end-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What &ldquo;year-end&rdquo; really means for the books.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Year-end is the point where a running set of books has to become a <em>final</em> set of books. Through the year, bookkeeping keeps the day-to-day current; at year-end you reconcile every account to its December statement, review how the whole year was categorized, and add the accrual-side entries the daily work doesn&rsquo;t capture &mdash; depreciation, accruals, prepaids, and corrections. Then you confirm payroll and W-2s, prepare 1099s, and finalize the financial statements so the numbers actually tie out.</p>
      <p>Here&rsquo;s the honest line that this whole checklist sits behind: <strong>getting the books year-end-ready is not the same as filing your taxes.</strong> We &mdash; an independent ProAdvisor firm &mdash; finalize the books and hand a clean package to your CPA or tax preparer, who files your income-tax return. We don&rsquo;t file it. What a good year-end close prevents is the expensive version of January: a CPA billing hourly to clean up messy bookkeeping before they can even start the return. Clean books make that bill small. The one piece that <em>is</em> a filing on this list &mdash; the 1099-NEC &mdash; is a payer filing due January 31, separate from your income-tax return, and the checklist covers it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

